<br>
During the period now known as “the Holy Inquisition”, thousands of women were put to death (usually by burning, or under torture) for ‘witchcraft’.<br>
<br>
Although this was NOT a purely Catholic practice – many women also died during this period in ‘protestant’ England &amp; Wales - the systematic persecution of women during this period was primarily instigated &amp; perpetuated by the ‘Office of  The Holy Inquisition”, a  pillar of the Catholic Church, orchestrated through the office of the  “Grand Inquisitor” – the head of the Inquisition.<br>
<br>
Does the Inquisition still exist? <br>
<br>
Well, actually, yes it does.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   The body responsible for this persecution still exists today, although it is now known as the “Congregation for the Doctrines of the Faith” [CDF]: however, it is still the same institution – it hasn’t gone away.<br>
<br>
Bizarrely, the institution was still known as “The Holy Inquisition” until the latter half of the 20th Century (until 1962, to be precise), when it’s name was changed and the office of “Grand Inquisitor” became the office of “Prefect” of the Congregation.<br>
<br>
This office is currently held by Cardinal Ratzinger, who made the headlines a couple of years ago by publicly stating that the Church should remain open to the possibility of extra- terrestrial life. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 0] --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif ALT="0]"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Is the Church also open to the possibility that women can play an equal role in society?  Does it still hold to the biblical injunction that “Thou shalt not permit a sorceress to live” [Exodus 22:18] ?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
What do you think – were the witch trials simply the product of mass-hyteria and the sexist/ misogynistic attitudes of the time. wipped up by paranoid, reactionary religious institutions … how far has society/  religious institutions etc really moved on??  Do the same attitudes still exist, but maybe reflect themselves in different ways today…<br>
<br>
I’d be interested to know what people think!<br>
<br>
Paul<br>
